## Chapter 6: Treasuries, Savings Bonds, and Federal Agency Paper

### Overview of U.S. Government Debt Instruments

Four distinct types of U.S. government debt:

- **Treasury securities** (bills, notes, bonds, TIPS) — sold at auction by the Federal Reserve Bank
- **Zero coupon bonds** — created by investment bankers from Treasury bonds
- **Savings bonds** (Series EE and Series I) — sold directly to individuals
- **Federal agency debt** — bonds issued by federal agencies with implicit government backing

### What Makes Treasuries Unique

**Safety and quality paradox**: Treasuries are common yet high quality

- Direct obligation of U.S. government (the ultimate insurer)
- Safer than insured accounts if rating safety among government-backed issues
- Since 1985: long-dated Treasuries not callable before maturity — more generous call protection than any other debt instrument
- Most liquid securities available — trade with lower markups than any other debt instrument

**The baseline for all bond pricing**:

> "Before buying any other fixed-income security, you should check out the yield of a Treasury with a comparable maturity. Professionals do. Every single debt instrument is priced by professionals off Treasuries."

- Never buy a security with maturity comparable to a Treasury unless additional yield (spread) compensates for additional credit risk
- Treasuries are ideal for risk-averse investors or those without time for portfolio management

**Performance advantages**:

- **Flight to quality buying** — During turbulent markets, investors sell other assets and buy Treasuries. Example: 2008 financial panic saw stocks and bonds collapse while Treasuries soared
- **Call protection** — Boosts return of long-dated Treasuries whenever interest rates decline significantly

**Tax advantages**:

- Taxable at federal level
- **Exempt from state and local taxes**
- In high-tax states, adds 50-60 basis points (approximately ½ of 1%) to yield
- Short-maturity Treasuries (under five years) may occasionally be competitive with tax-exempt municipal paper on after-tax basis

### Treasury Bills

**Maturity**: One year or less
**Current offerings**: 3-month, 6-month, 1-year
**Minimum denomination**: $10,000, with $5,000 multiples thereafter

**Structure**: Non-interest-bearing instrument
- Sold at discount from par
- Redeemed at par at maturity
- Yield = difference between discounted price and face value

**Yield quotation methods**:

1. **Discount rate** — based on one-time premium at redemption (simple interest)
2. **Bond-equivalent yield basis** — accounts for opportunity to reinvest and earn interest-on-interest; actual annualized return is higher

The bond-equivalent yield is 10-20 basis points higher than discount rate and enables comparison with coupon-bearing securities.

**Key characteristics**:

- **Zero credit risk**
- Interest rate risk negligible due to short maturity
- Yield on shortest bills = proxy for risk-free rate of return
- Institutions use them as cash equivalents
- **Book-entry form only**
- Most liquid of all instruments — can be sold anytime in secondary market

**Limitations**:

- Not appropriate as long-term investments
- Over long periods, total return lower than riskier investments
- Reinvestment risk very high

### Treasury Notes

**Maturity**: 2 to 10 years
**Current offerings**: 2-year, 3-year, 5-year, 7-year, 10-year

**Price volatility**:

- Fluctuates more than T-Bills in response to interest rate changes
- Smallest changes for 2-year notes, increasing gradually with maturity length
- Interest rate risk remains modest under 5-year mark but rises gradually thereafter

**Yield advantage**: 50-150 basis points more than T-Bills (depending on yield curve shape)

**Tax efficiency in inverted yield curves**:

- When short-term yields exceed long-term yields, Treasury notes (2-5 years) may yield more than municipal bonds on after-tax basis
- Inversions occurred in 1987, 1988, and 2000

**Historical performance**: **Ibbotson Associates study** (1926-1997):
- Average annual total return of Treasury notes: **5.3%**
- Compared with 5.2% for longer-dated Treasuries
- Higher return due to lower price volatility in response to interest rate changes

**Current uncertainty** (as of writing):

- Very steep yield curve
- 5-year maturities yielding ~60% of 10-year bond and 40% of 30-year bond
- Future performance depends entirely on direction of interest rates and yield curve shape
- Suggests considering "laddering" strategy (see Chapter 14)

> "What can be said with certainty is that notes continue to have a significantly higher yield than T-bills; and that if you hold the notes until they mature, you will recover invested principal, in full."

### Treasury Bonds

**Maturity**: 10 to 30 years
**Current offerings**: 10-year and 30-year bonds at auction (15- and 20-year bonds no longer sold)
- Any maturity available in active secondary market

**Call protection**: Not callable for 25 years — far more generous than corporates or munis

**Interest rate risk exposure**:

- Significant for long-dated Treasuries
- Current rates (as of writing): 3-4% for 10-year, 4-5% for 30-year
- Can earn 80-85% of 30-year yield by staying at/under 10-year maturity, reducing interest rate risk significantly

### Inflation-Indexed Securities (TIPS)

**Introduced**: 1997 by U.S. Treasury
**Full name**: Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities (TIPS)
**Purpose**: Assure real rate of return even with inflation; protect purchasing power

**Similarities with conventional Treasuries**:

- Backed by full faith and credit of U.S. government
- Sold at quarterly auctions
- Fixed-rate coupon paid twice yearly
- Available in 5-year, 10-year, and 30-year maturities
- 10-year fixed coupon has ranged from 4.25% (early auctions) to 1.375% (January 2010)

**Unique feature — inflation adjustment**:

- **Face value adjusted periodically** based on **Consumer Price Index for All Urban Consumers (CPI-U)** from Bureau of Labor Statistics
- Monthly CPI-U announcement creates ~1 month lag in price adjustment
- Over time, inflation adjustment results in face value rising at rate of inflation
- **Inflation adjustment applies to both principal AND coupon payments**

**How TIPS work** (Exhibit 6.1 example):

Hypothetical 30-year TIP with $10,000 face value, 3% coupon, 2.5% average inflation:

- **First coupon payment**: ½ of 3% × $10,000 = $150
- **After year one**: Face value rises 2.5% to $10,250
- **Second coupon payment**: ½ of 3% × $10,250 = $153.75
- **After 10 years**: Principal ≈ $12,800; coupon payment ≈ $192 twice/year
- **After 30 years**: Redemption value ≈ $20,975; coupon payment ≈ $314.62 twice/year

With 2.5% inflation and 3% interest, nominal return = 6-7% over 30-year period
**Real rate of return**: Historically ~3% above inflation rate

**Deflation protection**:

- Treasury guarantees final bond value will not be less than par or initial price at issue
- During 2009, CPI-U briefly went negative (−2.78%)
- If sustained deflation occurs, TIP holder has protection
- At maturity: redeemed at adjusted value of principal or initial face value, whichever is higher

### TIPS: Volatility

**Initial assumptions proved wrong**:

- Expected to be less volatile than conventional bonds — FALSE
- Expected to perform better during rising rates than declining rates — MISLEADING

**Reality**: TIPS highly unpredictable and complex

- Daily price changes result from TWO factors:
  1. Daily change in inflation factor (very minute price change)
  2. **Daily changes in interest rate levels and direction** (dominant factor)

- Over weeks, months, or years: **interest rate fluctuations have swamped inflation adjustment**
- **More volatile** than conventionally structured bonds of same maturity

**Explanations for higher volatility**:

1. Lower coupon relative to conventional bonds → longer duration → higher volatility
2. TIPS price sometimes moves on **inflation expectations** rather than actual inflation

**Divergent movements**:

- Example (beginning of 2004): 10-year TIPS yield declined ~40 basis points; conventional 10-year bond yield rose ~30 basis points
- Interest rates occasionally move in opposite directions

**Summary of cash flows**:

- Hold TIPS to maturity at auction → matures at value reflecting inflation adjustments throughout bond life
- Buy in secondary market or sell before maturity → price may be higher or lower based on daily TIPS price fluctuations

### TIPS: "Phantom Income" and Taxes

**Major drawback**: Tax treatment

- **Inflation adjustment reflected in daily market value** but IRS does not pay out adjustment until maturity
- Inflation adjustment = **"phantom income"**
- **Taxed annually** even though income not received for many years

**Reinvestment difficulty**: Interest income from TIPS is low, making reinvestment challenging with modest amounts invested

### TIPS versus Coupon Treasuries

**Question**: Should you buy 10-year TIPS or 10-year conventional Treasury note?
**Answer**: Nobody knows.

**Yield comparison**:

- TIPS interest yield typically ~200 basis points lower than conventional Treasury
- But yields are not equivalent
- Conventional Treasury yield = implicit inflation rate + interest rate payment
- **Real rate of return** = nominal rate minus inflation rate

**Breakeven rate concept**:

- Rate that results in equivalent total returns for both bond types
- Example: TIP coupon 2%, conventional Treasury 4%
  - If inflation = exactly 2% → total returns equal
  - If inflation > 2% → TIPS better due to inflation adjustment
  - If inflation < 2% → conventional T-Note better due to higher interest payments

**Long-term certainty** (10+ years):

- TIPS will parallel inflation rate
- TIPS outperform conventional bonds **only if inflation higher than breakeven rate** over holding periods
- Short periods (1-2 years): no way to predict which has higher total return

### Buying TIPS

**Simplest method**: Purchase directly at Treasury auctions via **TreasuryDirect** program through noncompetitive tender
- Minimum purchase: $1,000
- Maximum per individual at one auction: $5 million
- TIPS purchased before January 2007 = "Legacy TIPS"
- Older TIPS available in secondary market

**Recommendation**:

- Poor short-term investments (high volatility)
- For inflation protection: **buy and hold, don't trade**
- Tax features virtually dictate purchase only in **tax-sheltered accounts** (IRAs, retirement accounts) — eliminates annual tax on phantom income

### Buying Treasuries: TreasuryDirect

**TreasuryDirect program**: Simplest option for purchasing U.S. Treasury securities
- Allows accounts for individuals and "entities" (trust funds, estates)
- Purchase amounts: as little as $1,000 with $1,000 increments
- **Website**: TreasuryDirect.gov

**Advantages**:

- **Eliminates all transaction costs**
- Individuals receive same yield as institutional investors
- All Treasury securities consolidated in one account
- Banking directly with the Fed

**Account setup**:

- Entirely online at TreasuryDirect.gov
- Provide taxpayer ID, email address, password
- Link to bank account or commercial bank/brokerage firm
- Fed automatically debits account on auction day
- Interest payments and matured principal wired directly to designated account
- No fees unless account exceeds $100,000 in securities (then $25 annual fee)

**Purchasing process**:

- Submit "**noncompetitive tender**" — agree to purchase maturity at average auction yield
- Yield = average of all competitive tenders from dealers purchasing billions
- All securities sold in book-entry form only
- Can participate in any Fed auction

**Features**:

- Interest payments automatically wired
- Matured principal automatically deposited
- Can choose to automatically reinvest or withdraw cash
- All securities held in one central account regardless of maturities
- Access via Web or toll-free phone

**Sell Direct feature**:

- Enables selling Treasuries before maturity
- Fed obtains quotes from several brokers, sells at highest quote
- Proceeds deposited automatically
- Modest fee: currently $45

**Superiority over mutual funds**:

- Buying individual securities and holding to maturity guarantees full principal redemption
- Bond mutual funds may not return full principal (see Chapter 12)

**Auction information**:

- Most accurate info on Treasury Direct website
- Tentative 3-month calendars published: February, May, August, November
- Minimum: $100 for any security, increments of $1,000, up to $5 million

**Estimating probable yield**: Check most recent Treasury yield curve on Investinginbonds.com for desired maturity

**Purchasing through banks/brokers**:

- Available if no online access
- Fees modest: no higher than $25-$50 per transaction
- Many brokers eliminated fees for purchasing Treasuries at auction
- **TreasuryDirect only sells new issues** — for older outstanding issues or zeros, use broker

**TreasuryDirect website quality**: Detailed, continually updated, easy to use — best source of information about U.S. government debt

### Zero Coupon Bonds

**Nickname**: "Strips" (describes creation process)
**Origin**: 1982 investment banks separated revenue streams (coupons-only and principal-only) from Treasury bonds and repackaged as distinct securities

**Structure**:

- No interest coupons received
- Sold at very deep discount from par
- Matures at par
- Difference between discounted price and par = interest earned

**Interest-on-interest built in**:

- Final lump sum calculated to include interest-on-interest as if coupons reinvested periodically at yield-to-maturity rate
- Why zeros "multiply like magic": $197 in zero at 8.3% → $1,000 in 20 years

**Main difference from conventional Treasury**:

- **No reinvestment risk**
- Actual dollar return known and guaranteed
- Reinvestment automatic and efficient

**Disadvantages**:

- Expensive to purchase small sums — **markups high and variable** dealer to dealer
- Short maturities (under 5 years): conventional coupon Treasury may be better buy
- Locking in yield-to-maturity only advantageous if zero has particularly attractive yield

**Tax treatment**:

- Interest accrued (earned) **taxed annually as "imputed interest" or "phantom interest"** even though no payments received before maturity
- Suitable mainly for **tax-sheltered accounts** (IRAs, Keoghs) and accounts taxed at low rates (children in low tax bracket)

**Extreme volatility**:

- Basic explanation: **duration**
- Zeros have no coupons → duration = maturity (far longer than ordinary coupon bonds with same maturity)
- Volatility of zeros much higher than ordinary coupon bonds with same maturity

**Exhibit 6.2**: Price changes for zero vs. coupon bonds (both yielding 7%)

Interest rates rise 50 basis points (7% → 7.5%):
- 2-year: coupon −0.9%, zero −1.0%
- 5-year: coupon −2.1%, zero −2.4%
- 10-year: coupon −3.8%, zero −4.7%
- 30-year: coupon −5.9%, zero −13.5%

Interest rates rise 200 basis points (7% → 9%):
- 30-year zero: declines 43.8% ($4,380 per $10,000)
- 30-year coupon bond: declines 20.6% ($2,060 per $10,000)

Interest rates decline 100 basis points (7% → 6%):
- 30-year zero: rises 25% ($2,500 per $10,000)
- 30-year coupon bond: rises approximately 13.8%

Interest rates decline 200 basis points (7% → 5%):
- 30-year zero: price rises **79%** ($7,900 per $10,000)
- 30-year coupon bond: appreciates 79%

**Key insight**: Price changes are larger if interest rates decline than if they rise (at same magnitude). Anyone anticipating interest rate declines buys zeros.

**Note on timing**: Illustrated changes assume instantaneous yield change. In reality, changes of this magnitude take months or years. Must adjust for time passage — if rate change occurs 5 years after purchase, 10-year bond becomes 5-year bond.

**Historical precedent**: Changes illustrated are plausible
- September 1998 to December 1999: 30-year bond went from 4.78% to 6.75%
- Early 2000: long bond reversed, declining to ~5.75% between January and end of March

> "In sum, while there is no risk to principal if you hold a Treasury zero to maturity, if you want to resell it before it matures, its value may have gone up a great deal or may have declined significantly."

### Zeros for Investment Purposes

**Ideal for tax-sheltered accounts** (IRAs, Keoghs) when investing small sums periodically

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter 6: U.S. Government Securities (continued)

### Zero Coupon Bonds: Strategic Uses (continued)

**Third use: Saving for known future needs**
- Zeros lock in total return at purchase, making them ideal for college savings or other target dates
- Can select maturities to coincide with specific future needs (retirement year, tuition payments)
- Build an annuity by laddering zeros to mature sequentially (every year for 15-20 years)
- Problem: **Phantom income** from Treasury zeros generates annual taxes even though no cash is received
- Solution: **Municipal zeros** (covered in Chapter 7) avoid tax on phantom income for high-income investors

> "Because reinvestment rates are locked in, the total return when the zero matures is known and guaranteed." — On predictability of zeros for future planning

### U.S. Savings Bonds

Two current types: **Series EE** and **Series I** (HH bonds no longer issued)

**Key shared features:**
- **Impeccable credit quality** — direct U.S. government obligations
- **Attractive tax features** — interest exempt from state and local taxes
- Tax deferral on all interest until redemption
- **Education tax exclusion** — interest may be entirely tax-free if used for college expenses
- Available in small amounts ($25 minimum) up to large purchases ($1 million maximum)
- Resources: savingsbonds.gov and publicdebt.treas.gov

### Series EE Bonds

**Structure:**
- Sold at 50% of face value ($50 buys a $100 bond)
- **Accrual bonds** — no interest payments until redemption
- Since 1997, earn 90% of average five-year Treasury auction rate (previous six months)
- Interest rates reset every six months
- Original maturities: 8-17 years, but most extend automatically for up to 30 years total

**Redemption rules:**
- Can redeem anytime after six months
- **Penalty for early redemption:** forfeit last three months of interest if redeemed before five years
- Taxes deferred until bonds are cashed, minimum five-year hold required for full tax benefit

**Purchase limits:**
- Online: up to $1,000 face ($500 cost)
- **EasySaver** payroll deduction: $25 minimum ($50 face), $5,000 maximum ($10,000 face)
- Maximum annual purchase: $15,000 purchase price ($30,000 face amount)
- No commissions

**Tracking value:**
- **Savings Bond Wizard** (government web tool)
- **Savings Bonds Earnings Report** (government web tool)
- Check current worth and earnings rate online or at local bank

### HH Bonds

Discontinued September 2004. Older bonds still outstanding may be redeemed through local banks with signature guarantee.

### Series I Bonds

**Key concept:** "I" = inflation. I bonds resemble **TIPS** — they're inflation-indexed accrual bonds.

**How they work:**
- Accrual bond (monthly interest added, paid at redemption)
- **Dual-rate structure:** fixed rate + variable semiannual inflation rate
- Fixed rate set at purchase, remains constant for life of bond
- Inflation adjustment resets every six months (May and November) based on **CPI-U**
- Rates are compounded (not simply added) — formula explained on Treasury website
- In deflation, bond value stays at pre-deflation level (floor protection)

**Example (November 2009):**
- Combined rate: 3.36%
- Fixed component: 0.30%
- Semiannual inflation component: 1.53%

**Historical rates during 2008 panic:**
- May 2008: 0% fixed rate (lowest ever)
- November 2008: 0.7% fixed
- May 2009: 0.10% fixed
- Combined rate remained above 3% despite low fixed components

**Major advantages over TIPS:**
- Interest rate at issue guarantees minimum return (floor)
- **Value cannot decline** — I bonds don't trade in secondary market (unlike TIPS, which fluctuate)
- TIPS values fluctuate with interest rate changes; I bonds do not

**Purchase and redemption:**
- Face amounts: $50 to $5,000
- Purchased at face value (pay $50 for $50 bond)
- Buy via TreasuryDirect, local bank, or **EasySaver** payroll plan
- 30-year maturity, redeemable anytime after six months
- **Small early redemption penalty:** forfeit three months interest if cashed within five years

### I Bonds Performance Data

**Exhibit 6.3** shows earnings for bonds held 1-10 years:
- Recent four-year period (low rates): 3.36%-4.28% current earning
- 1998-2000 vintages (higher fixed rates): 6.00%-6.53% current earning, cumulative returns 6.03%-6.51%
- Older issues continue earning higher rates because fixed component was higher when purchased
- 10-year cumulative returns have been solid

**Smart Exchange program:** TreasuryDirect account holders can convert Series E, EE, and I paper savings bonds to electronic securities in "Conversion Linked Account"

### I Bonds as Deferred-Tax Retirement Vehicle

**Author's sales pitch:** I bonds offer retirement plan features rarely discussed:
- Invest $50 to $5,000 per purchase, up to $10,000 per calendar year
- **Guaranteed minimum rate** set at purchase, plus inflation adjustment every six months
- **In deflation, minimum rate remains in effect**
- **In rising rates, bond value will not decline** (unlike any other bond, including Treasuries in secondary market)
- Interest and interest-on-interest compound tax-deferred until redemption
- Can withdraw any amount anytime after six months
- Money can compound for up to 30 years
- Exempt from state and local taxes
- **Highest credit quality** (zero default risk)
- **No commissions**
- Buy online, through payroll deduction, or at local bank

> "I have just repeated all the features I described above, because those are the features of I bonds. They bear repetition because this product is a sleeper: I have seen almost no mention of it in the financial press." — Author emphasizing I bonds are under-promoted

**Why brokers and banks don't push I bonds:**
- Brokerage firms can't sell them (no commissions)
- Banks don't profit from them (compete with CDs)
- Despite being superior to many tax-deferred products (annuities), they remain obscure

**Recent limitation (major change):**
- Maximum purchase reduced to $10,000 per year per Social Security number
- $5,000 electronic form + $5,000 paper securities
- Each partner in a couple can invest $10,000
- Prior limit: $60,000 electronic + $30,000 paper = $90,000 per person ($180,000 per couple)
- **New profile:** clearly targeted at middle class rather than affluent investors
- Still recommended for safe, predictable portion of retirement savings, especially for fixed-income investors

### Savings Bonds for Education: The Education Tax Exclusion

**Both EE and I bonds qualify:**
- Proceeds used for college tuition and fees = **tax-free** (no federal taxes)
- Only tuition and fees qualify — not room, board, books, miscellaneous expenses

**Requirements:**
- Bonds must be in parent's name (not child's)
- **Income restrictions** apply (caps reset annually, pegged to inflation)
- 2008 limits: full exclusion for joint incomes under $100,650
- Partial exclusions for incomes up to $130,650 ($67,100 and $82,100 for single filers)
- Current guidelines published in IRS Form 8815

**Under normal conditions:** Savings bonds generally more advantageous than municipal bonds for education savings (especially given middle-income targeting)

## Chapter 7: Municipal Bonds

### What Is Unique About Municipal Bonds?

**"Munis"** issued by city, county, and state governments, plus entities with public purpose (electric utilities, universities, hospitals).

**Chief attraction:** Federally tax-exempt. If issued in your state, usually also exempt from state and local taxes (**triple tax-free**).

**Market characteristics:**
- Only sector where primary buyers are individual investors
- 1.4 million issues outstanding
- Relatively uncomplicated once you understand basics
- **Credit safety second only to Treasuries**
- Default rate remains extremely low despite publicized defaults

**2007-2009 volatility:**
- 2008 was worst year in municipal bond market history
- 2009 was one of the best — most sectors rallied strongly

**Major recent developments (2008-April 2010):**
1. **Failure of major bond insurance firms** — almost total disappearance of bond insurance from muni market
2. **Build America Bonds (BABs)** — new taxable municipal bonds, initially temporary but proving popular (proposals to extend/make permanent under Congressional consideration)
3. **New ratings scale adoption** — will upgrade most general obligation bonds and many others
4. **Web expansion:** investinginbonds.com and EMMA.msrb.org bring transparency and data to muni investors

### Should I Buy Munis? (Taxable-Equivalent Yield)

**"Taxaphobia":** Many investors buy tax-exempt bonds even when it makes no economic sense.

**Taxable-equivalent yield formula:**

taxable-equivalent yield = tax-exempt yield / (1 - tax bracket)

**Example (39% tax bracket, 5% muni YTM):**
- Calculation: 0.05 / (1 - 0.39) = 0.082 or 8.2%
- You'd need to earn 8.20% in taxable security to match the 5% muni

**Example (15% tax bracket, same 5% muni):**
- Calculation: 0.05 / (1 - 0.15) = 5.88%
- You may earn more buying taxable instrument at this bracket

**Exhibit 7.1** provides taxable equivalent yields at various federal brackets (15%, 28%, 31%, 36%, 39.6%)

**Resources:** Investinginbonds.com and FINRA.org/marketdata have calculators for tax-equivalent yields

**High-tax states (NY, CA, MA, MN):**
- Demand for tax-exempt paper often so high that out-of-state munis (federally tax-exempt but not state-exempt) may yield more after taxes than in-state munis
- Compare yields on **taxequivalent basis** at state level
- Calculators at Investinginbonds.com and FINRA.org enable state-level comparisons (enter federal bracket + state name)

**Additional considerations:**
- Treasury and some federal agency debt also exempt from state taxes
- In high-tax states, Treasuries or certain agencies may net more than municipals after taxes
- Particularly true for very short maturities (two years or less) where muni yield curve is steeply upward sloping
- For discount muni bonds, YTM includes capital gains component (federally taxable) — if discount is substantial, calculate impact of capital gains taxes on total YTM

**Rule of thumb:**
- Highest tax brackets benefit most from tax-exempt bonds
- Lowest brackets do not
- Middle depends on taxable vs. tax-exempt yield relationship at time of purchase (changes continually) and current tax laws
- If tax laws change or income changes, recalculate whether munis still make sense

### Credit Quality: General Obligation vs. Revenue Bonds

**Two varieties:**
1. **General obligation (GO) bonds** — backed by taxes and user fees
2. **Revenue bonds** — backed by revenues from specific enterprises

**General obligation bonds:**
- Issued by states, cities, counties for schools, sewers, road improvements
- Interest paid from taxes and user fees
- Supposedly backed by "unlimited taxing power" of issuer

**Revenue bonds:**
- Issued by public-function enterprises (electric utilities, toll roads, airports, hospitals, special "authorities")
- Interest paid from enterprise revenues (electricity fees, tolls, patient revenues, etc.)


<!-- pp. 161-180 -->

## The Rise and Fall of Bond Insurance

### Origins and Purpose

**Municipal bond insurance** emerged in the late 1980s as a marketing tool, not a necessity. Municipal bonds have the **lowest default rates** of any debt instrument next to Treasuries. Insurance companies (**MBIA, AMBAC, FGIC, FSA**) guaranteed payment if issuers defaulted, extending their AAA ratings to insured bonds. This transformed bonds with lower ratings into AAA-rated securities — "making lemonade out of lemons."

- Bond insurers carefully screened bonds to insure only those unlikely to default
- Insurance remained highly profitable with minimal losses for many years
- AAA rating promoted liquidity and attracted individual investors
- Lower interest costs for issuers as insurance spread declined
- By early 2007, **over 50% of municipal bonds** came to market with insurance

### Why Bond Insurers Failed

Around 2000, insurers expanded beyond municipal bonds into **taxable bonds tied to subprime mortgages**. When the 2007 financial crisis hit, losses mounted and threatened their capital base. Three major firms (**Ambac, MBIA, FGIC**) were downgraded to **several notches below investment grade** — effectively "junk" status. These firms essentially stopped writing bond insurance.

- **Assured Guaranty** (which acquired FSA in 2009) remains the only meaningful presence, rated AAA by S&P and AA3 by Moody's
- **Berkshire Hathaway** announced entry in 2008 but has not insured any municipal bonds and has no plans to do so
- Financial difficulties stemmed from **taxable bond portfolios**, not municipal bonds
- Downgrades depressed the municipal market for over a year, but ultimate failures did not permanently damage the muni market

### Impact on Ratings

Many bonds were rated AAA solely because of insurance. After insurers were downgraded, questions arose about how rating agencies would handle insured bonds.

**Fitch's solution**: Rate municipal bonds based on their **underlying rating** (the issuer's own credit quality). If underlying rating is higher than the insurer's rating, use the underlying rating. If lower, use the insurer's rating. Other agencies followed suit.

- Most municipal bonds had underlying ratings **higher than bond insurance firms** after downgrades
- Term "underlying rating" now appears in municipal bond rating information
- For bonds continuing to be rated AA or A, price declines from insurer downgrades should have been minor
- Only bonds with underlying ratings below investment grade faced steeper declines

### Long-Term Market Effects

Despite concerns, the lack of insurance did not permanently impair issuers' ability to bring bonds to market. A **record number of municipal bonds** were issued in 2009, and yields actually came down as munis rallied.

Demand for bond insurance collapsed: only about **6% of muni bonds** came to market with insurance in 2009, compared to over 50% in 2007. Some speculation exists that firms may create a new type of credit-enhancement business for smaller or marginal issuers.

By fall 2008, the financial crisis became the bigger story, relegating bond insurer failures to the back pages.

## "Recalibrations" of Municipal Bond Ratings

### Rationale for Change

In April 2010, **Moody's and Fitch** announced plans to change their entire rating scales for municipal bonds. The change was justified by **default history**: municipal bonds have significantly lower default rates than corporate bonds with the same letter ratings.

> "Historical default experience shows that the risk of default for municipals is significantly lower than that of taxable debt."

- 2007 Moody's study: general obligation bonds rated barely investment grade experienced default rates **lower than AAA corporate bonds**
- 2009 Moody's study: between 1970 and 2009, rated municipal bonds experienced **54 total defaults** (less than 0.07%)
- Most defaults occurred in housing and healthcare sectors

The old scales overstated municipal bond risk by using the same letter symbols (AAA, AA, A, BBB, etc.) as corporate debt, implying comparable default risk when actual experience showed municipals were far safer.

### The "Global" Scale Movement

For years, observers called for a **"unified" or "global" rating scale** based on actual default experience across all bond sectors. A global scale would give municipals **significantly higher ratings** to reflect their lower default rates.

- Congressional hearings in 2010 gave further impetus
- March 2010: Fitch and Moody's announced they would adopt global rating scales
- **S&P** declined to follow initially, continuing to use a global scale all along

### Rating Changes Announced (April 2010)

**Fitch** (April 5, 2010) re-rated most municipal bonds:
- Bonds rated AAA remain AAA
- Most **general obligation bonds** upgraded one, two, or even three notches
- Some **revenue bonds** upgraded one or two notches
- 38,000 bonds "recalibrated"; about 3,750 CUSIPs not previously rated AAA now rated AAA; over 7,500 CUSIPs moved up to AA

**Moody's** (April 19, 2010) rolled out new scale gradually:
- At least 14 states would be rated at least AA
- State of California bonds upgraded three notches, from Baa1 to A1

Private purpose or "enterprise" revenue bonds (airports, sports stadiums, nursing homes) least likely to see changes — always compared to similar corporate enterprises.

### What "Recalibrations" Mean

Term emphasizes these "upgrades" **do not denote a change in financial strength** of issuers. Rather, they're based on the belief that old scales overstated the riskiness of municipal bonds.

> Analogous to a college professor deciding exam grades were too severe — an exam graded as B before will now be graded as A+. The answers haven't changed, but the professor is giving higher grades.

### Market Impact and Confusion

**Potential benefits**:
- Upgrades allow some institutional buyers (prohibited from buying bonds below specified minimums) to buy more munis
- Should promote liquidity
- Issuers hope for lower borrowing costs

**Uncertainties**:
- Newly upgraded AAA bonds may trade with somewhat higher yields than bonds that were AAA all along (similar to how insured AAA bonds traded at higher yields than "AAA naturals")
- Timing ironic: rating changes occur as budgets of many issuers under enormous strain, with daily headlines about cities and states forced to cut budgets
- Changes bound to result in confusion, at least initially

## Safest, Highest Quality Bonds

### Pre-Refunded Bonds ("Pre-Res")

**Pre-refunded bonds** are **as safe as Treasuries** — they are backed by Treasuries held in escrow.

**How pre-refunding works**:
- Municipality issued bonds years ago at higher interest rates (e.g., 6%)
- Original call provisions require waiting several years before calling
- Municipality "refinances" by issuing new bonds at current lower rates (e.g., 4%)
- Proceeds from new 4% bonds purchase **U.S. Treasury securities** placed in **escrow account**
- Treasury bond coupons pay interest on old 6% bonds (now called "refunded" bonds)
- At first call date, remaining escrow assets redeem the refunded bonds

**Advantages**:
- Totally free of default risk — monies held in escrow and invested in Treasuries
- Initial rating jumps to AAA (though issuer must apply for re-rating)
- Generally trade like AAA bonds
- Maturities tend to be short; **low interest rate risk**
- Trade at a premium; offer **higher cash flow** and somewhat higher yields than similar maturity/credit quality bonds

### State Bond Banks and Umbrella Programs

States issue bonds (primarily **school bonds**) on behalf of localities through well-run, highly rated **bond banks** operating as quasi-insurance. Examples include Maine, Virginia, New York, and New Jersey.

- Some bond banks pledge state aid payments for debt service if local school districts face financial difficulty
- **Texas Permanent School Fund (PSF)**: $22 billion fund guaranteeing bonds issued by school districts (rated AAA)
- **"Double-barreled" bonds**: essential services like water/sewer with both general obligation backing and dedicated revenue

### High-Quality Criteria

- Any bond rated **AA to AAA on its own merit** is extremely safe credit
- Actual default experience of municipal bonds has been extremely low
- **Shorter maturities** (not longer than 10 years) add protection — less visibility about possible economic changes
- April 2010 marks the month rating scales changed — investors may inquire whether a rating is pre- or post-April 2010

## Letters of Credit (LOCs)

**Letters of credit** are issued by banks and insurance companies as credit enhancement, similar to bond insurance but with less protection.

- An LOC does **not obligate the bank to actually take over interest payments**
- Rather, it's a **line of credit** obligating the bank to lend money to the issuer if cash is insufficient for interest payments
- LOCs vary in degree of obligation: some **irrevocable**, others obligate bank only under certain stipulated conditions

LOC backing used to be fairly common but is no longer a major factor in the municipal market. Now used primarily with **variable rate demand obligations** (short-term debt purchased by institutions).

## Taxable Municipal Bonds

Not a mistake — some municipal bonds have always been taxable. Primarily issued for **private purposes** (not deemed essential to public good): sports facilities, certain housing bonds. This was a diminishing category until recently.

## Build America Bonds (BABs)

**Build America Bonds** are a new type of **taxable municipal bond** created by the Obama administration's 2009 stimulus legislation. Unlike prior taxable munis, proceeds are for **public purposes** (primarily infrastructure projects).

### Structure and Subsidy

Bonds benefit from a **subsidy directly from the Treasury**:
- Issuers can choose a **direct subsidy of 35%** of coupon interest from Treasury
- OR buyers can benefit from a **35% tax credit**

For issuers, even though bonds are taxable (higher interest expenses), the 35% subsidy reduces net interest cost to **below that of tax exempt bonds**.

### Characteristics and Appeal

**Institutional investors** initially bought BABs, attracted by:
- High credit quality — taxable bond with **higher credit quality** than many corporate bonds
- Interest rates competitive with corporate bonds
- Same appeal for individual investors buying BABs in **tax-deferred plans** (IRAs, 401Ks)
- Even attracting **foreign buyers**; Toronto-based firm launched municipal bond fund dedicated to BABs
- Ratings will be upgraded due to recalibrations, making them even more popular

### Program Timeline and Features

- Initial legislation: BABs issued only during **2009 and 2010**
- Proposals to extend program but reduce subsidy (from 35% to 30% in 2013)
- Proposals to make program permanent
- BABs issued primarily with **longer maturities (20-30 years)** — likely in secondary market for many years

**Call provisions**: BABs are callable. Because they compete with taxable corporate debt, call provisions often match those for corporate bonds.

- Frequent use of **"make whole" call provisions** to protect original buyer against calls resulting in principal loss
- Make whole provision: if called, bond redeemed at the higher of par or a formula price (typically yield of 10-year Treasury plus 30-50 basis points)
- Protects buyer if bonds purchased at or close to par — worst case is call at par with no principal loss

**Unintended consequence**: BAB popularity has reduced the **supply of long-term tax exempt bonds**.

## Municipal Bonds with Special Features

### Municipal Notes

Issuers issue debt with **maturities under three years**: **revenue anticipation notes (RANs)**, **tax anticipation notes (TANs)**, or **bond anticipation notes (BANs)**. These securities secure interim financing from anticipated revenues (taxes or bonds).

- Ratings: **"MIG 1" and "MIG 2"** by Moody's; **"SP 1" or "SP"** by Standard & Poor's
- Purchased mainly by institutional investors, but available in amounts as low as **$10,000**
- If yield curve is normal (upward sloping), notes yield **50 to 100 basis points more** than tax-exempt money market funds
- Municipal note yield curve usually more sharply upward sloping than Treasuries, so tax-exempt note yields are comparatively low
- Limit purchases to those with **impeccable credit quality**

### Municipal Zeros

Sold under various names: **"municipal multipliers," "principal appreciation bonds," "capital appreciation bonds,"** or zeros. Issued at deep discount from par, redeemed at par at maturity. Difference between issue price and par represents specified compounded annual yield.

**Key differences from Treasury zeros**:
- **Federally tax exempt** — no annual tax on "phantom" interest
- **Credit quality varies** with issuer and is critical (no interest paid until maturity)
- **Subject to call** — called at stipulated **discounts from par**, not at par
- Volatility comparable to Treasury zeros, particularly high for long maturities

**Secondary market now more active** — markups comparable to other munis. Volatility makes zeros **high-risk investments** if planning to resell. Appropriate mainly if planning to **hold to maturity**.

### Bonds with Put Provisions

A "put" is the **exact opposite of a call**. Gives purchaser the option of **tendering bond back to issuer** at stipulated intervals or dates at par.

- Protection for bondholder: if interest rates rise, can redeem without loss and reinvest at more attractive rate
- **Less volatile** than other long-term bonds; normally trade at or close to par

**Disadvantages**:
- **Coupon interest usually lower** than bonds with similar maturity — total return may be lower
- If interest rates decline, put bonds **appreciate much less** than other long-term bonds

### "Supersinkers"

A variety of **housing bonds** with specifically designated maturities singled out for **early retirement** if mortgages are prepaid. Some bonds may be called early. Name derives from monies accumulating in a "sinking fund." **Retirement date is uncertain** because prepayments are unpredictable.

**Attractive feature**: Since no specific call date, the yield and price are determined by the **maturity date**, not by the uncertain call date. Supersinkers normally mature well before their maturity date — purchaser earns a **long-term yield on a short-term security**.

**Caution**: Be very cautious if a supersinker is selling at a **high premium** — early call would result in a loss of principal.

## Municipal Bond Pricing

### Call Risk

Munis (mainly long-term) are **subject to call** — issuer may redeem before maturity date.

**Typical call provisions for 30-year bonds**:
- Initial call date **10 years after issue**, at price slightly above par (typically 101)
- Several additional consecutive call dates (in 15 years at 102, and so on)
- **Housing revenue bonds** may have unusual call features (bonds may be called as early as a few years after issue if proceeds not needed for mortgages)

**Call likelihood**:
- Issuers likely to call if interest rates drop substantially
- Higher and more attractive yield to investor = more expensive interest for issuer = more likely to be called
- Be particularly careful to **investigate call provisions for bonds selling at a premium**
- Doubly careful for **housing bonds selling at a premium** — sometimes subject to extraordinary calls
- Broker should quote both **YTM and yield to first call date** (yield-to-call usually lower than YTM)
- If bond is called, **yield-to-call becomes the actual return**

### "Dollar" Bonds and "Basis" Bonds

- **"Dollar bonds"**: price quoted in dollars
- **"Basis bonds"**: price quoted "to the basis" — YTM is quoted, buyer works backward from quoted yield to compute price

### The Dated Date

The date on which the bond **begins accruing (earning) interest**.

### Markups

> "Let the buyer beware" or "what the market will bear."

For individual investors, bonds priced "fairly" have **commission costs** varying from:
- Under 1% ($100 per $10,000 par) for actively traded issues with short maturities and high credit quality
- About 4% ($400 per $10,000 par value) for inactively traded bonds with long maturities
- Under stress, markups above 4% are not uncommon

**Small lots** (under $25,000 par value):
- Considered a pain by brokers and **marked up accordingly**
- Makes them particularly expensive to sell
- Expression: they "punish the coupon" — commission costs for selling small lots are extremely high
- Dealers who buy small lots from you do so with understanding they are doing you a favor
- Dealer will be **anxious to get rid of small lots** and will price them attractively for resale
- You can sometimes find attractive prices if you want to **buy a small lot** — but don't plan to resell

**Author's pricing experiment** (20 years ago):
- Called seven different firms to see prices for selling inherited small lots
- High-quality, widely traded New Jersey Turnpike bond; very controversial credit (Philadelphia); infrequently traded issues
- Prices were **closest on New Jersey Turnpike bonds** (author lives in New Jersey and bonds are actively traded)
- Even on this lot, offers varied by **150 basis points** on a price of 98
- Selling a $40,000 par value bond translates into a **price difference of $612** between highest and lowest offer
- Largest difference on out-of-state housing bond: **375 basis points** (almost 4% or $1,500 on $40,000 lot)
- Some dealers refused to bid on lesser-known names

**Modern pricing research** (Internet era):
- While researching pricing on Internet (Bond Desk electronic platform), author tracked same bond on different dealer Web sites
- Different brokers using same electronic platform offered markedly different prices for the **same bond**:
  - 101 by two firms
  - 103 by another firm
  - 103 to 105 by still another firm
- Dealers mark up prices **independently**; dealer markups can vary
- Electronic platforms routinely mark up the price based on instructions of the dealer selling the bond

## Shopping for Municipal Bonds Using the Internet

Markups for municipal bonds continue to be hidden. Is there a way to determine if you're being quoted a fair price?

### Step One: Get an Overview of the Market

If not following interest rates regularly, first get an overview of yields currently available. Visit **Investinginbonds.com** → "The Municipal Market at a Glance."

**Exhibit 7.2** (April 23, 2010) shows:
- Yield curve was **steeply upward sloping** (yields starting well below 1%, rising to well over 4%)
- Yields shown are for **AAA bonds** (lowest yields)
- Yields for lower quality credits would be higher
- These yields are **highly approximate** — averages, culled nationwide

### Step Two: Do Some Comparison Shopping

Look at online broker Web sites to see bonds being offered for sale. Most allow **targeted search** with criteria:
- State where you live
- Range of acceptable maturities
- Minimum credit quality ratings
- Additional criteria: minimum yield or minimum coupon

**Typical listing** (Exhibit 7.3) shows:
- **Quantity**: total number of bonds for sale for that issue
- **Min Qty**: minimum number of bonds you can order
- **CUSIP number**: unique identifier for additional information
- **Issue name** and additional details (tax status, call provisions)
- **Coupon**: set when bond was issued
- **Price**: posted by dealer selling the bond
- **Yield**: YTM that would result if bond bought at listed dealer price (actual yield slightly lower after broker commission)

### Understanding "Material Events"

**"Material events"**: Warning that somewhere in the bond's history, events occurred resulting in a change in credit rating and hence price.

- If phrase occurs along with bond insurance firm name, assume material event is **downgrade of bond insurance firm**
- Look for phrase **"underlying rating"** — the bond's current rating
- Same phrase "material events" could refer to event affecting **financial strength of issuer**
- **Never buy any bond** listed with this phrase without finding out what it refers to

### Tax Status

**BABs** now included in many listings for municipal bonds. Check carefully whether listing is for:
- Tax exempt muni
- BAB (taxable at federal level)
- Some bonds subject to **alternative minimum tax (AMT)**

### Bond Insurers in Listings

Bond insurers continue to be listed, creating confusion:
- Most bond insurance firms have been downgraded to below investment grade
- Phrase "material events" often applies to downgrade of bond insurance firm, rather than issuer

### Detailed Bond Information (Exhibit 7.4)

Clicking on individual issues brings up more detailed screen showing:
- Dates when bond may be called
- Dates when interest is paid
- Multiple yields: **yield-to-maturity (YTM)**, **yield-to-call**, **current yield**

### Bond Rating

Ascertaining ratings is now **much more confusing** due to:
- Downgrades of bond insurers
- Recalibrations that took place in April 2010
- Often see **more than one rating**
- Need to figure out why there's more than one rating and what different ratings mean

**Source**: BondDesk, an electronic platform, identified as the source of the additional details with disclaimer about accuracy.

<!-- pp. 181-200 -->

## Bond Ratings: Understanding Underlying vs. Insurer Ratings

### Decoding Rating Complexity After 2008

- **Underlying rating** = issuer's credit quality before bond insurance
- Insured bonds show TWO ratings: underlying (lower) and insurer rating (higher)
- Example: **Bayonne bond** had Baa1 underlying rating, Aa1 after **AGMC** insurance
- **Moody's Global Recalibration (April 2010)**: upgraded Bayonne from Baa3 to Baa1 — two notch jump
- **AGMC (Assured Guaranty Municipal Corporation)** was one of few insurers still rated AA3 post-crisis
- Historical ratings archived under "material events" — only most recent ratings matter
- Post-2008 insurer downgrades + 2010 recalibrations make determining actual ratings "detective work"
- Small issuers often pay for only one rating (Moody's OR S&P/Fitch, not both)

> "Determining the actual ratings of municipal bonds will require some detective work."

### The Many Meanings of Yield

- **Never compare bonds by price alone** — focus on **yield-to-maturity (YTM)** when comparing bonds
- YTM assumes: you hold to maturity, reinvest coupons at the same rate
- For income investors who spend (not reinvest) coupons: **current yield** may be more relevant
- Example: 3% YTM bond with 4% current yield (premium bond) suits income seekers better
- **Low coupon bonds rarely get called** — call risk correlates with coupon level
- Yield-to-call and yield-to-worst matter only if the bond has high coupons

### Using Investinginbonds.com for Price Data

- **Investinginbonds.com** launched 1991, began publishing all muni trades in 2005
- Trade data available within 15 minutes of execution
- Provides TWO types of data: (1) individual bond trade history, (2) comparable bond searches

#### Trading History of Individual Bonds

- **High trade volume is NOT a red flag** — many quality munis trade infrequently (< 12 times/year)
- Low trading frequency just means buy-and-hold investors, not distress
- Example: **New Jersey Transportation Bond (CUSIP 646136FB2)** — 1,852 trades listed
- Trades classified as: (1) Purchase from customer (investor selling), (2) Sale to customer (investor buying), (3) Inter-dealer
- **Inter-dealer price = market price** — investors pay markups above this
- **Markup calculation**: highest price (customer buy) minus lowest price (customer sell to dealer)
- Real example (March 2010): same $50K bond lot sold at 112.596 and 114.975 — **2% price difference, 4% dealer markup**
- One investor paid $56,298, another paid $57,487 for identical bonds on same day
- Appropriate markup for intermediate maturity: **1-2%**; longer maturities: **2-4%**

> "Clearly, one customer overpaid for this bond."

#### Finding Comparables

- Search "Municipal Market-at-a-Glance" → filter by state, maturity, yield, coupon
- **Data overload problem**: all trades listed within 15 minutes creates overwhelming detail
- True comparables require: same credit quality, virtually identical maturities, very similar call provisions
- Additional factors: lot size, interest rate direction, dealer inventory needs
- Sort by yield to find bonds with near-identical yields, then filter by maturity and credit rating

### EMMA.msrb.org: Official Statements and Continuing Disclosure

- **EMMA (Electronic Municipal Market Access)** launched by **MSRB (Municipal Securities Rulemaking Board)** July 2009
- Official repository for muni bond information and disclosure
- Trade activity data originates from MSRB (same as Investinginbonds.com)
- Can search bonds without CUSIP — use issuer name + maturity
- Three tabs: Official Statement, Continuing Disclosure, Trade Activity

#### Official Statement (OS) Analysis

- **OS contains all information disclosed to rating agencies**
- Rating agencies base ratings primarily on OS content
- Focus: revenues available for debt service, adequacy to cover obligations
- For revenue bonds: examine **debt service coverage ratio**
- Example: **City of Bayonne $55.3M School Bonds** OS shows bond counsel opinion, tax treatment, maturity schedule

> "Reading the OS is not the most fun you will have in your day, but it has all the information you will need to evaluate the financial strength of the issuer."

#### Rating Complexity in Official Statements

- OS shows rating at issuance — may be outdated for bonds issued pre-2008
- If bond traded in secondary market pre-2008, rating likely changed
- **Post-May 2010**: dealer websites should note recalibration upgrades and dates
- **MSRB (planned 2011)**: will include complete rating information on EMMA
- **Continuing disclosure**: annual financial statements posted on EMMA (started July 2009)
- "Material events" affecting bond value must be disclosed
- Many CUSIPs show no continuous disclosure yet (site too new as of writing)

#### EMMA Alert Feature

- Free alert system: type CUSIP + email to receive notifications about owned bonds
- Alerts cover material events affecting bond value

### Talk to a Broker: The Human Element

- Always investigate trade history and comparables before buying
- **Target price**: closest to inter-dealer price (market price)
- Customer buys close to inter-dealer prices exist — larger lots usually get better deals
- Brokers can double-check bond details (ratings, call provisions, tax treatment)
- Broker listings may contain errors or be outdated — never assume online info is accurate
- **Rating confusion is common**: bonds showing AAA ratings that are no longer applicable
- Many outdated AAA ratings were from insurers downgraded to below investment grade

#### Broker Value Propositions

1. **Verification**: double-check all critical bond features
2. **Rating clarity**: navigate underlying vs. insurer ratings, recalibrations
3. **Better pricing**: access to "fair value" pricing data, some firms prohibit sales outside 3% pricing band
4. **Negotiation**: brokers can bargain with dealers for better prices
5. **Inventory access**: firm inventory vs. dealer electronic platforms often have better pricing
6. **Due diligence requirements**: increased emphasis on brokers checking fair value post-NASD crackdown

> "Firms expect you to call and they expect you to bargain."

- Broker tactics: offer to buy bond at better price to show "bargain," steer to firm inventory with better markup

### Buying at Issue

- **New issue advantages**: uniform pricing at par for all syndicate dealers for several days
- Prices and yields particularly attractive — dealers anxious to sell
- Longest possible call provisions
- Major brokerage firms and regional specialists have access to new issues
- Smaller firms and discount brokers may not — ask where to find them

## Selecting Municipal Bonds

### Alternative Minimum Tax (AMT) and "De Minimis" Tax

#### Alternative Minimum Tax

- **Tax Reform Bill of 1986** subjects certain "nonessential" munis to **AMT**
- Only bonds issued after August 7, 1986 designated as nonessential
- AMT applies only if investor's tax bracket triggers alternative minimum tax calculation
- **AMT-subject bonds yield more than other munis** (compensating for potential taxation)
- For those NOT subject to AMT (most investors not in highest brackets), AMT bonds offer higher yield
- Calculation: compute taxes two ways (standard + AMT method), pay the higher
- **Avoid AMT bonds if you might be subject to AMT** — check with accountant

#### "De Minimis" Tax

- Applies to discount bonds bought below threshold, then redeemed at par
- **Threshold = years to maturity × 0.25**
- Example: 10-year bond threshold = $975 (10 × 0.25 × $1,000 par)
- Price gain below threshold treated as **ordinary income** (not capital gain) at sale/maturity
- Lowers real yield for de minimis bonds
- Rule applies to original issue discount bonds AND secondary market discount bonds
- High tax bracket investors should check with accountant before buying deeply discounted munis

#### Capital Gains and Tax Loss Swaps

- Selling munis creates capital gains or losses (taxable events)
- **Tax loss swap**: sell declining bonds, buy comparable bonds to generate tax loss
- Swaps discussed in **Chapter 14**
- For high tax brackets, large portfolios, or active traders: consult tax accountant

> "Investinginbonds.com has added an extensive discussion of tax information for all tax issues pertaining to municipal bonds."

### Discounts versus Premium Bonds

**Common misconception**: avoid premium bonds because you "lose" the premium at maturity

**Reality**: Premium bonds generally yield MORE than discount bonds (all else equal)

#### Why Premium Bonds Yield More

- YTM for premium bond based on redeeming at par — the premium is NOT lost
- Discount bond YTM includes anticipated capital gains (taxable)
- Premium bond entire dividend yield is tax-free; discount bond has taxable capital gain component
- **Net yield on discount may be lower than quoted YTM** (after taxes)
- Premium bonds have **higher coupons** → higher cash flow for reinvestment
- Makes more sense when long-term rates are low (reinvest at higher rates if rates rise)
- **Investors avoid premiums** → usually offered at higher yields than comparable discount bonds
- **Premium bonds less volatile** than discount bonds (protects principal if rates rise)

#### Premium Bond Advantages

- Higher cash flow
- Lower volatility
- Tax-free income vs. taxable capital gains

**Warning**: watch call provisions on premium bonds — **housing bonds often have special early calls**

### Overall Strategy Recommendations

#### Traditional Advice (30-Year AAA Bonds)

- "Buy AAA bonds, 30-year maturities, maximum call protection"
- Objection: **long maturities = maximum interest rate risk**
- Current environment: high-quality 30-year munis yield 4.1-4.5% (historically very low)
- Selling long-maturity bonds incurs very high markups

#### Author's Alternative Strategy

**For maximum income and safety:**

- **8-12 year maturity munis**: yields 3-3.8%
- Higher yields available on **high-quality premium bonds**
- **Interest income 80-85%** of longer maturity bonds
- **Significantly lower volatility**
- **Lower markups** if you need to sell

**Safety hierarchy (in order):**
1. Pre-refunded bonds
2. Bonds with credit enhancements (bond bank, double-barreled revenue backing)
3. Bonds rated AA or higher
4. Stick to maturities ≤10 years to reduce volatility

**For premium bonds:** only buy if yields particularly attractive, only buy 30-year bonds with highest credit quality

#### Small Portfolio Strategy (<$50,000)

- Difficult to diversify individual munis (high transaction costs)
- **Consider pre-refunded bonds** (maximum safety, maturities under 7 years)
- Or **high-quality short-to-intermediate bond fund** (see **Chapter 12**)
- **Tax bracket check**: if under 25%, taxable bonds (Treasuries via Treasury Direct, I bonds, EE bonds) may yield more

#### Large Portfolio Strategy (>$50,000)

- Diversify across maturities and issuers
- Consult **Chapter 15** for additional strategies

## Summary

### Municipal Bond Market Status (2010)

**Positives:**
- Rating recalibrations (Fitch, Moody's) = vote of confidence in muni quality and safety
- Recalibrations promote liquidity
- Potential tax rate increases on affluent families would boost muni appeal

**Negatives:**
- Rising interest rate risk threatens long-term bond values
- Budget problems across many issuers
- Daily "Are municipal bonds safe?" headlines (misleading — due to widespread publicity of rare defaults)

> "All it takes is for one default to happen, with widespread publicity, for the entire sector to be tarred, even if this is grossly unfair, and totally misleading."

**Author's advice unchanged**: buy high-quality, short-to-intermediate bonds

### Checklist: Questions to Ask Before Buying Municipal Bonds

- When does the bond mature?
- Who is the issuer?
- What is the rating?
- If insured, what is the "underlying" rating?
- When was rating issued? Pre- or post-May 2010 recalibration?
- What is revenue source for debt service? Is it adequate?
- For revenue bonds: what is debt service coverage ratio? What is YTM?
- Is bond callable? Sinking fund provisions? When? At what price?
- If callable: yield-to-call? Yield-to-worst?
- When did bond last trade? At what price? Customer buy, sell, or inter-dealer?
- If no recent trades: can I find comparables?

### Key Resources

- **Investinginbonds.com** and **EMMA**: best free resources
- **The Bond Buyer**: $2,850/year subscription (for portfolios >$500K)

## Appendix: The New York City Default (1975)

### The Default Event

- **April 1975**: NYC deferred interest payment on short-term note (cash crunch)
- Technically a default, highly publicized
- Interest payment ultimately made — no permanent loss
- Bonds sold by investors declined in value due to publicity
- Some NYC officials claim it was never a "real default"

### Resolution: Municipal Assistance Corporation (MAC)

- **September 1975**: **Financial Emergency Act** → **Emergency Financial Control Board**
- Three-sector cooperation: unions (pension funds), state (cash advances), banking community
- **MAC (Municipal Assistance Corporation)** created to issue bonds on behalf of NYC
- **MAC bonds were NOT NYC obligations** — backed by NYS taxing power
- Revenue sources: special lien on NYC sales tax + stock transfer tax (not NYC's general taxing power)

### Financial Warning Signs (Pre-Default)

- Revenue shortfalls from economic decline
- Inability to contain spending within revenues
- Poor fiscal management (funding long-term expenditures via short-term borrowing)
- Widely reported in press — downgrade should have been anticipated

### MAC Bonds as Investment Opportunity

- Issued at **10% yields** vs. 8% for comparable maturity/credit (200 bps premium for bad publicity)
- Very solid investment from the start: strong revenue sources, excellent debt service coverage
- Debt service coverage predicted to strengthen further
- 1990 coverage: **11× on first lien bonds, 4-5× on second lien bonds**
- Initially rated A, upgraded to AA by 1990 due to excellent coverage history

**Lesson**: Sensational headlines don't equal actual credit risk — NYC's well-publicized troubles created opportunity for informed investors.

